g, elaborating, testing, and building calculating machines. He explores the writings of philosophers, engineers, and craftspeople, showing how they thought about technical novelty, their distinctive areas of expertise, and ways they could coordinate their efforts. In doing so, Jones argues that the conceptions of creativity and making they exhibited are often more incisive—and more honest—than those that dominate our current legal, political, and aesthetic culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCalculatorsxHistory. 0aComputersxHistory. 0aTechnologyxHistory. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aBlaise Pascal.  aCharles Babbage.  aCharles Mahon, 3rd Earl Stanhope.  aGottfried Wilhelm Leibniz.  aartisanal knowledge.  acalculating machines.  aeighteenth century.  aintellectual property.  anineteenth century.  aseventeenth century.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107109840 cprintz978022641146040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226411637423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226411637/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles